<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter subject="Biology" id="322" name="Chemical Coordination and Integration">
    <easy>
        <question>
            <text>Glands that lack ducts and release secretions directly into blood are ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Endocrine glands (Ductless)</option><option id="B">Exocrine glands</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Secretions are called hormones.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Chemicals produced by endocrine glands that act as inter-cellular messengers? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Hormones</option><option id="B">Enzymes</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Produced in trace amounts and are non-nutrient chemicals.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hypothalamus is the ____ part of diencephalon (forebrain).</text>
            <option id="A">Basal</option><option id="B">Dorsal</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Contains several groups of neurosecretory cells called nuclei.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hormone that stimulates secretion of pituitary hormones is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Releasing hormone (e.g. GnRH)</option><option id="B">Inhibiting hormone</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>GnRH stimulates gonadotrophins release.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hormone that inhibits release of pituitary hormones is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Inhibiting hormone (e.g. Somatostatin)</option><option id="B">Releasing hormone</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Somatostatin inhibits growth hormone from pituitary.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Pituitary gland is located in a bony cavity called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Sella turcica</option><option id="B">Orbit</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Attached to hypothalamus by a stalk.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Pituitary gland is divided anatomically into ____ and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Adenohypophysis / Neurohypophysis</option><option id="B">Cortex / Medulla</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Adenohypophysis is the anterior pituitary; Neurohypophysis is posterior.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hormone that stimulates abnormal growth of body? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Growth Hormone (GH)</option><option id="B">TSH</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Over-secretion leads to Gigantism; low leads to Dwarfism.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>TSH stimulates synthesis and secretion of thyroid hormones from ____ gland.</text>
            <option id="A">Thyroid</option><option id="B">Adrenal</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>TSH = Thyroid Stimulating Hormone.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>ACTH stimulates secretion of ____ from adrenal cortex.</text>
            <option id="A">Glucocorticoids</option><option id="B">Adrenaline</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>ACTH = Adrenocorticotropic Hormone.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hormone that stimulates growth of mammary glands and milk formation? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Prolactin (PRL)</option><option id="B">Oxytocin</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Oxytocin works on milk ejection later.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hormone that regulates skin pigmentation? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">MSH (Melanocyte Stimulating Hormone)</option><option id="B">Melatonin</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Acts on melanocytes in skin.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hormone stored and released by Neurohypophysis (produced in hypothalamus) is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Oxytocin / Vasopressin (ADH)</option><option id="B">GH / TSH</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>They are transported axonally to posterior pituitary.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hormone that acts on smooth muscles and stimulates contraction during birth? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Oxytocin</option><option id="B">Vasopressin</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Often called 'birth hormone'.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hormone that prevents water loss through urine? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Vasopressin (ADH)</option><option id="B">Oxytocin</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Acts on kidneys to reabsorb water.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Pineal gland is located on the ____ side of forebrain.</text>
            <option id="A">Dorsal</option><option id="B">Ventral</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Secretes Melatonin.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Melatonin regulates the 24-hour diurnal rhythm of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Sleep-wake cycle</option><option id="B">Digestion</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Also influences body temp and metabolism.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Thyroid gland is composed of two ____ located on either side of trachea.</text>
            <option id="A">Lobes</option><option id="B">Hormones</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Connected by a thin flap of tissue called isthmus.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Essential element for normal rate of thyroid hormone synthesis? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Iodine</option><option id="B">Iron</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Deficiency leads to Goitre.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hypothyroidism during pregnancy can lead to defective development of baby called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cretinism</option><option id="B">Myxedema</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Leads to stunted growth and mental retardation.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Thyroid hormones increase BMR, which stands for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Basal Metabolic Rate</option><option id="B">Blood Muscle Ratio</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Essential for generating body heat.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>TCT (Thyrocalcitonin) is a protein hormone that ____ blood calcium levels.</text>
            <option id="A">Lower (Hypocalcemic)</option><option id="B">Increase</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Antagonistic to PTH.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Number of parathyroid glands in humans is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">4 (on back side of thyroid)</option><option id="B">2</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>One pair in each lobe of thyroid.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>PTH (Parathyroid Hormone) ____ blood calcium levels.</text>
            <option id="A">Increases (Hypercalcemic)</option><option id="B">Decreases</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stimulates bone resorption (dissolution).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Thymus gland plays major role in development of ____ system.</text>
            <option id="A">Immune</option><option id="B">Digestive</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Secretes Thymosins.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Thymosins help in differentiation of ____-lymphocytes.</text>
            <option id="A">T</option><option id="B">B</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Provide cell-mediated immunity.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Thymus decreases in size with ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Age</option><option id="B">Weight</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Reason for weak immune responses in old people.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Adrenal gland is located on the ____ part of each kidney.</text>
            <option id="A">Anterior (Suprarenal)</option><option id="B">Posterior</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Composed of two types of tissues: Medulla and Cortex.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Adrenal medulla secretes Adrenaline (Epinephrine) and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Noradrenaline (Norepinephrine)</option><option id="B">Cortisol</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Commonly called catecholamines.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Adrenaline is also called 'hormone of ____' or 3F hormone.</text>
            <option id="A">Fight-Flight-Fright</option><option id="B">Digestion</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Secreted in response to stress/emergency.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Catecholamines increase heart beat, strength of heart contraction and rate of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Respiration</option><option id="B">Digestion</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Prepare body for physical activity.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Primary glucocorticoid in humans is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Cortisol</option><option id="B">Aldosterone</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Involved in carbohydrate metabolism.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Primary mineralocorticoid in humans is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Aldosterone</option><option id="B">Cortisone</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Regulates water and electrolyte balance.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Pancreas is a composite gland (both exocrine and endocrine) called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Heterocrine / Mixed</option><option id="B">Holocrine</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Endocrine part is Islets of Langerhans.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Alpha cells of Islets of Langerhans secrete ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Glucagon</option><option id="B">Insulin</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Hyperglycemic hormone.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Beta cells of Islets of Langerhans secrete ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Insulin</option><option id="B">Glucagon</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Hypoglycemic hormone.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Primary male sex organ is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Testis</option><option id="B">Ovary</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Located in scrotal sac.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Leydig cells (interstitial cells) produce hormones called ____ (mainly testosterone).</text>
            <option id="A">Androgens</option><option id="B">Estrogens</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Control male secondary sexual characteristics.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Primary female sex organ is ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ovary</option><option id="B">Testis</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Produces ova and steroid hormones.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Easy 40 complete?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Done.</explanation>
        </question>
    </easy>
    <medium>
        <question>
            <text>Hormone that stimulates development of ovarian follicles? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">FSH (Follicle Stimulating Hormone)</option><option id="B">LH</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Part of gonadotrophins.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hormone that triggers ovulation and transformation of follicle to corpus luteum? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">LH (Luteinizing Hormone)</option><option id="B">FSH</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Known as 'ovulatory hormone'.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Corpus luteum secretes mainly ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Progesterone</option><option id="B">Estrogen</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Essential for maintenance of pregnancy.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hormones of adrenal medulla work in ____ to autonomic nervous system.</text>
            <option id="A">Synergy (Sympathetic)</option><option id="B">Antagonism</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Augment sympathetic responses.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Glucagon acts on ____ to stimulate glycogenolysis.</text>
            <option id="A">Hepatocytes (Liver cells)</option><option id="B">Muscle cells</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Converts glycogen back to glucose.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Insulin acts on hepatocytes and ____ (fat cells) to increase glucose uptake.</text>
            <option id="A">Adipocytes</option><option id="B">Neurons</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Triggers glucose storage/utilization.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Prolonged hyperglycemia leads to a complex disorder called ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Diabetes Mellitus</option><option id="B">Diabetes Insipidus</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Due to insulin deficiency or resistance.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>ANF (Atrial Natriuretic Factor) is secreted by ____ in response to high blood pressure.</text>
            <option id="A">Heart wall (Atria)</option><option id="B">Kidney</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Causes vasodilation.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Erythropoietin is secreted by JGA cells of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Kidney</option><option id="B">Spleen</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stimulates RBC formation (Erythropoiesis).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Gastrointestinal hormones include Gastrin, Secretin, ____ and GIP.</text>
            <option id="A">CCK (Cholecystokinin)</option><option id="B">Insulin</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Regulate digestion and enzymes.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Secretin acts on exocrine pancreas and stimulates secretion of ____ and bicarbonate ions.</text>
            <option id="A">Water</option><option id="B">Enzymes</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Helps in neutralizing stomach acid in duodenum.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>CCK acts on ____ and gall bladder to stimulate secretion of bile and enzymes.</text>
            <option id="A">Pancreas</option><option id="B">Stomach</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stimulates gall bladder contraction.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>GIP stands for ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Gastric Inhibitory Peptide</option><option id="B">Glucose Induced Protein</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Inhibits gastric secretion and motility.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Water soluble hormones that interact with membrane-bound receptors? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Protein / Peptide hormones</option><option id="B">Steroid hormones</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Cannot cross cell membrane; require second messengers like cAMP.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Lipid soluble hormones that interact with intra-cellular receptors? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Steroids / Thyroid hormones</option><option id="B">Catecholamines</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Can cross membrane; usually regulate gene expression.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Secondary messengers include cAMP, IP3 and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Ca2+ (Calcium ions)</option><option id="B">Na+</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Amplify the hormone signal inside the cell.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Adrenal cortex is divided into three layers: Reticularis, Fasiculata and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Glomerulosa</option><option id="B">Medulla</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Ordered from inner to outer? No, Glomerulosa is outermost.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Excessive secretion of growth hormone in adults leads to ____ (severe disfigurement).</text>
            <option id="A">Acromegaly</option><option id="B">Gigantism</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Often due to pituitary tumor; hard to diagnose early.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Exophthalmic goitre (Grave's disease) is a form of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Hyperthyroidism</option><option id="B">Hypothyroidism</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Autoimmune; characterized by protrusion of eyeballs.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Deficient production of cortical hormones leads to ____ disease.</text>
            <option id="A">Addison's</option><option id="B">Cushing's</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Alters carb metabolism; leads to acute weakness/fatigue.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Testosterone is a ____ hormone.</text>
            <option id="A">Steroid (Androgen)</option><option id="B">Peptide</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Derived from cholesterol.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Glucogenesis is the formation of ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Glucose from non-carbohydrate sources (e.g. lipids/proteins)</option><option id="B">Glycogen</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Stimulated by Glucagon and Cortisol.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Catecholamines stimulate breakdown of ____ and ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Glycogen / Lipids (and proteins)</option><option id="B">Vitamins</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Rapidly increases blood glucose level.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of these is NOT an endocrine gland?</text>
            <option id="A">Salivary gland (Exocrine)</option><option id="B">Thyroid</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Releases secretions into ducts.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hormone that regulates Ca2+ balance in body? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">PTH and TCT (Antagonistic)</option><option id="B">Insulin</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Crucial for nerve/muscle function.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Melatonin is derived from amino acid ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Tryptophan</option><option id="B">Tyrosine</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Tyrosine is precursor for Thyroid and Catecholamines.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Islet of Langerhans constitutes only approx ____% of pancreatic tissue.</text>
            <option id="A">1 - 2</option><option id="B">50</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Rest is exocrine (acini).</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hormone that acts on Leydig cells and stimulates androgens? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">LH (ICSH in males)</option><option id="B">FSH</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>ICSH = Interstitial Cell Stimulating Hormone.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hormone that acts on Sertoli cells and stimulates spermiogenesis? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">FSH</option><option id="B">LH</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Involved in male gamete maturation.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Relaxin is secreted by ____ during later stages of pregnancy.</text>
            <option id="A">Ovary (and Placenta)</option><option id="B">Pituitary</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Softens pelvic ligaments.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Feedback mechanism: High blood glucose inhibits ____ and stimulates ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Glucagon / Insulin</option><option id="B">Insulin / Glucagon</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Brings level back to normal.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Human chorionic gonadotropin (hCG) is produced by ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Placenta</option><option id="B">Ovary</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Used as basis for pregnancy tests.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Is heart considered an endocrine organ?</text>
            <option id="A">Yes (minor one, secretes ANF)</option><option id="B">No</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Many non-endocrine organs have endocrine functions.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hypodermic stimulation of sweating is mediated by ____? No. Catecholamines ____ sweating.</text>
            <option id="A">Increase</option><option id="B">Decrease</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>'Cold sweat' of fear.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Does thyroid gland secrete only T3 and T4?</text>
            <option id="A">No (also secretes Calcitonin)</option><option id="B">Yes</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Calcitonin is from parafollicular cells.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Which of these glands is present only in females?</text>
            <option id="A">Ovary</option><option id="B">Pineal</option><option id="C">phi</option><option id="D">None</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Testis unique to males.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
            <text>Hormone that acts on gastric glands and stimulates HCl? ____.</text>
            <option id="A">Gastrin</option><option id="B">Secretin</option><option id="C">None</option><option id="D">D</option>
            <answer>A</answer><explanation>Secreted by G-cells of stomach.</explanation>
        </question>
        <question>
